<p>I have a VS2013 solution with 2 projects. One is a c++/cli dll. The other is a c# console app. The dll contains a class whose ctor takes a <code>const WCHAR *</code> parameter. In the C# app, I tried to create an instance of the class. I used a string literal for the ctor parameter. The build error is:</p>  <p>The best overloaded method match for <code>MyLib.MyClass.Myclass(char*)</code> has some invalid arguments</p>  <p>I have 2 questions.</p>  <ol> <li><p>Why does VS2013 think the parameter is <code>char*</code> instead of <code>WCHAR*</code>?</p></li> <li><p>How can I pass a string from c# to C++?</p></li> </ol>  <p>The purpose of this work is to see if using a C++/cli dll is easier than just using dllimport/pinvoke. </p>